# UI Component Architecture

Client components live under `app/src/components/` in four tiers, each its own
directory. A component may only depend on components in the tiers above it in
this list (views can use everything; primitives use nothing but each other).

- **primitives/** — smallest building blocks (e.g. `Button`, `Input`). Tailwind /
  shadcn styling, no app or domain knowledge.
- **composites/** — reusable combinations of primitives (labeled fields, cards,
  dialogs). Still domain-agnostic.
- **features/** — domain-aware pieces wired to data/state (Apollo hooks, mutations,
  router). Compose composites and primitives.
- **views/** — top-level, route-level screens, suffixed `View`, mounted by the
  router. Compose features, composites, and primitives.

Put a new component in the lowest tier that fits.

## Purity: primitives & composites get 100% of their state via props

Primitives and composites MUST be pure presentational components — all state and
behavior arrives through React props. They must NOT:

- call app/state hooks (`useQuery`, `useMutation`, `useContext`, router hooks, …);
- hold business state (`useState`/`useReducer`); purely-internal UI helpers like
  `useId` are fine;
- import from `@/auth`, `@/generated`, or `@/apollo`.

Data fetching, mutations, and routing belong in **features** and **views**, which
pass data and callbacks down as props.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — a composite fetching its own data
function UserBadge() {
  const { data } = useQuery(MeQuery); // hooks/data not allowed here
  return <span>{data?.me?.username}</span>;
}

// ✅ GOOD — state comes in through props
function UserBadge({ username }: { username: string }) {
  return <span>{username}</span>;
}
```
